{"id_":"97ef1ebf-1306-459b-9a1e-e25d8ab7eb75","metadata":{},"excludedEmbedMetadataKeys":[],"excludedLlmMetadataKeys":[],"relationships":{"SOURCE":{"nodeId":"7yNNTlp100H99q+B9Vrhv3026JYByb6KjqnL1ZZMLY8=","metadata":{},"hash":"ce79e2T9LumbxUSW84E+0YdI7yBpz3RVCQDMeIAolzw="},"PREVIOUS":{"nodeId":"a3f42b50-677d-4473-8a8b-7f8ddcfb9944","metadata":{},"hash":"xgBKyPQhfMYcqxkrJnzX4tXszvcYagvPFk4SzDbzvCk="}},"hash":"1u0RrlZeIxMmzTqP2NshEXPk/qpOI8sF7qC2UBMFgxw=","text":"For example, your headless CMS might have a different API endpoint for draft posts. If so, you can modify the API endpoint URL like
below:
export async function getStaticProps(context) {
  const url = context.draftMode
    ? 'https://draft.example.com'
    : 'https://production.example.com'
  const res = await fetch(url)
  // ... }
Thats it! If you access the draft API route (with secret and slug) from your headless CMS or manually, you should now be able to see
the draft content. And if you update your draft without publishing, you should be able to view the draft. Set this as the draft URL on your headless CMS or access manually, and you should be able to see the draft. Terminal (bash)https://<your-site>/api/draft?secret=<token>&slug=<path>","textTemplate":"","metadataSeparator":"
","type":"TEXT"}

